Beijing’s natural ecology continues to be good, attracting more than 500 wildlife cities to “settling” - the Middle New Network.
2020-07-26 05:03:17 Source: Beijing Youth News. Author: Wang Si-seok.
The natural ecology of the capital continues to be good, attracting wildlife cities to "settling."
Beijing has more than 500 species of wildlife.
Reporters of the Beijing Youth News (Reporter Wang Bin) have learned from the Urban Forest Greening Bureau that the species and quantities of wildlife have continued to grow in recent years as the natural ecological environment of the capital continues to improve.
At present, the number of terrestrial vertebrates living in Beijing has increased to over 500 species, including protected animals at the national level, such as maroons, black storks, and second-level protected animals at the national level, such as falcons, swans, cranes and thugs.
Whether planted in a single urban forest in two rings or embedded in a small wetland between buildings, it not only brings the citizens of the capital the joy of nature, but also attracts wildlife to “settling” in the city.
During the summer season, the Pine Hill National Nature Conservancy, located in the mountains of Yinshan in the north-west of Yingqing District, was vibrant.
One of them was hanging around the mountain and playing, and two of them were fighting each other.
In retrospect, a wild boar can't stop scratching its skin. The director of the National Directorate of Nature Reserves at Matsuyama introduced the fact that, by the end of 2019, 178 species of wildlife, including the State-level conservation of animal gold sculptures and the State-level protection of animal spoon chickens, falcons, and nearly a third of the city's wildlife species, were visible in the green sea, covering a total area of more than 6,200 hectares.
“In Matsuyama, wild animals are the true `masters' and our staff are, at best, other people's `guards'.”
In order to gain an understanding of wildlife in protected areas on the ground, there are more than 30 professional escorts on a daily basis, travelling along 16 well-defined protection routes, and a monthly roundabout, which takes almost a full day to reach the entire protected area.
“In the course of the inspection, not only are biological diversity records checked, but also the installation of artificial bird nests, the rescue of injured wildlife, the installation of wild infrared cameras, etc.”.
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in the Matsuyama National Nature Reserve to document the state of life of wildlife in the forest.
Illustratively, as the biodiversity of protected areas has increased over the years and wildlife has become more visible in the lens, leopard cats, thugs and thugs have become “resident guests” and the “opportunity” for the protection of animal falcons at the national level has increased.
Zhang Zhi Minh, Head of the Wildlife and Wetlands Conservation Division of the Beijing Gardens Greening Authority, reported that the number of terrestrial vertebrate wildlife in Beijing had increased from 461 in 1994 to more than 500 today, and that the range and number of wildlife in Beijing had continued to increase in recent years.
The increasing visibility of wildlife in cities is closely linked to the increasing greening of the capital city in recent years.
In particular, a new wave of million acres of afforestation was launched in 2018, proposing the restoration of urban ecosystems, the enhancement of the ecological function of green lands on forested lands and the promotion of the concept of “near nature”.
The plan seeks to interact with the surrounding greenfields and to make it easier for wildlife to “visit and visit” and to plant trees that animals love as honey and feeding plants.
