On 25 July, Xinning Xining Xining, Xinhua, a journalist (Jinjin Wang, journalist) learned from the five-way beam protection station of the Coco Sili administration of the Yangtze National Parks Administration in the Yangtzeen Park District, that monitoring showed that the Tibetan antelope who had previously travelled to the Lake Drone region in the heart of Coco Sicily was ending their labour and began to return to their homes with young children.
Surveillance of the five beams near the protection station showed that on 25 July, about 40 female herds, led by three herds, continued to move back through the 3002 km of the Blue Hide Road and the five Liangbei Bridge on the Blue Hide Railway.
The experts analysed that, in recent years, the number of hide-and-go-go-go-go-go-go-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba-ba.
The Deputy Researcher at the North-West Plateau Institute of Biology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences stated: “In the early stages of the relocation, Tibetan antelopes face a higher risk of being arrested, so that the number of cubs in the flock is relatively small and may even be absent.”
According to the Coco Siri Administration of the Yangtze National Parks Administration, the number of re-locations of Tibetan antelopes has generally increased year by year, from 4860 in 2019 to 338 in 2018.
Even the new statement: “It is expected that this year's return will be completed at the beginning of September, and the number of returns is expected to continue to increase”.
Tibetan antelopes are protected at the national level.
At the end of May of each year, Tibetan antelopes from the Qinghai trijiangsu, Tibet Pond and Xinjiang Alkin are going to produce lambs in Lake Trene, located in the heart of Coco Sicily.
Our Tibetan antelope protection expert, Wu Xiaomin, a researcher at the Institute of Animals of the Province of Shaanxi (North-West Institute of Endangered Animals), said: “The return of Tibetan antelopes is the process of returning to their habitat with young children after the completion of the female herd. The first group of returns from the land of origin is larger, but then the herds will return to their respective habitat according to different geographical populations and along different routes.”
In order to ensure the safe return of the Tibetan antelope herds, journalists were informed that the former Changjiri administration of the Yangjiang Parks Administration had arranged for staff to conduct continuous video monitoring and district patrols in the main areas of the relocation.
