So, what do we do in everyday life?
The experts suggested that summer days should avoid high-temperature periods and that it would be better not to walk or work in the hot sun before or after noon, as the sun is the strongest and the heat is more likely to occur.
If it is necessary to go out during this period, protection must be done, such as setting up an umbrella, wearing a hat, wearing sunglasses, with conditions that are best used to wear sunscreens to prevent sunburn.
Clothes are selected to the extent possible using light-coloured, gas-friendly cotton, as well as filamentary, and less penetrating fibre-based clothing, in order to avoid excessive sweating without the timely evaporation of the heat, which causes heat to catch heat.
In hot and hot weather, sufficient water should be prepared, used in good time, and water should not be used until it is thirsty, since once the thirst indicates that the body is already water-scarce, the drinking of water is controlled at 150 to 200 ml per drink, the drinking of warm and open water and the drinking of ice water.
Based on the high and low temperatures, average staff drink 1.5 to 2 litres of water per day, and high-temperature operators drink 3 to 5 litres per day.
When sweating is greater, some salt water can be properly replenished to compensate for loss of salt due to sweating.
In addition, the human body is prone to a shortage of potassium during the summer, which is an excellent source of drinking water.
Water-rich vegetables such as lettuce, cucumbers, tomatoes, and fresh fruits such as peaches, apricots, watermelons, melons, etc. can be used to supplement water by 80 to 90 per cent; dairy products can both replenish water and meet the nutritional needs of the body.
In addition, drinking products containing potassium, magnesium, etc. should be appropriately supplemented for people working in high-temperature environments.
