A small plane crashed in the Swiss Alps, and all four people on board were killed.
On July 25, local time, the Swiss police informed the media that a small aircraft had crashed in the Swiss Alps.
All two Swiss and two Austrians on board of the accident were killed.
According to a statement reportedly made by the canton of Wallis in southern Switzerland, a small aircraft crashed at an altitude of more than 3,000 metres near Mount Alpine in Valle, and relief personnel arrived at the crash site and confirmed that all four people on board had been killed.
According to the Valle State police, witnesses called the police at 12.25 p.m. on 25 November to report that they had witnessed a small plane falling from the sky.
A few minutes later, witnesses again informed the police that smoke had broken out at the crash site.
Upon being called to the police, the police quickly coordinated fire officers, medical and rescue personnel and took a helicopter to the scene of the accident.
When the rescue personnel arrived at the crash site, it was found that all four people on board had been killed.
The police verified that the victims of the accident included two Swiss men aged 50 and 66, as well as two Austrians aged 46 and 50.
The police indicated that they were currently investigating the cause of the crash in cooperation with the Swiss Transport Security Investigation Commission.
