The meeting was chaired by Malaysia, the host of this year's APEC Leaders Informal Meeting.
The joint statement issued after the meeting stated that the AEC member trade ministers recognized the importance of a free, open, equitable, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment in promoting economic recovery at this challenging time.
The parties undertake to ensure that emergency measures taken to respond to the epidemic are targeted, appropriate, transparent and temporary, do not create unnecessary trade barriers and disrupt global supply chains, while respecting World Trade Organization rules.
In his statement, the trade ministers of the APEC members committed themselves to strengthening cooperation to facilitate the flow of necessary goods and services, to promote connectivity through enhanced supply chain elasticity and to minimize disruptions to the movement of medical supplies, food and agricultural products in order to respond to the epidemic.
The APEC member trade ministers agreed on the need to discuss ways to reduce non-tariff barriers that restrict trade in essential commodities and reaffirmed their commitment to facilitate the necessary cross-border movement of people without prejudice to measures to stem the spread of the epidemic.
The Conference also issued a declaration on the promotion of the flow of essential commodities.
The declaration states that the economies will ensure that their trade measures in response to the epidemic are consistent with WTO provisions and undertake actions to reduce non-tariff barriers to trade, trade facilitation, etc., in order to facilitate the flow of goods necessary for the epidemic.
The Minister of International Trade and Industry of Malaysia, Azmin Ali, who chaired the meeting, said that, despite the impact of the epidemic, Malaysia remained committed to the success of this year's APEC Conference, and that the development of an APEC vision for cooperation beyond 2020 was proceeding in an orderly manner.
