The 3-year-olds were hit in the playground, and after they got paid, did they have a reason to sue the school?
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Rule of Law Journal
The playground's been smashed, and the kids will be fined and they'll sue the school.
□ Correspondent, Zhao Yifan
When he was playing in a university playground, he was accidentally hit in the head by Chen of the softball team during the pitching.
After Chen's compensation, Mr. Man, his father, as his legal representative, brought the school before the court, asking for an apology from the school where the performance took place, and for payment of medical expenses, moral damages, etc., in the total amount of $20,000.
Recently, the People's Court of the Haidian District of Beijing, after considering the case, decided to dismiss the plaintiff's application on the basis of its finding that the school had set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, that it had fulfilled its duty to provide adequate safety and security, and that Chen Xiao had paid compensation.
Mr. Wen complained that during his summer vacation in 2019, he had taken Man to play in the school playground, where he was trained by the softball team.
In order to avoid the risks involved, Mr. Wen, Mr. Man and many other small friends and parents operate in safe areas designated by the softball team.
However, Chen, a softball team player, then left during the pitching, causing the softball to fly across the net to the above-mentioned safe area and hit Little Man in the back of the brain.
Mr. Wen immediately took him to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with a head wound.
In Mr. Man's view, the school grounds facilities did not meet the relevant safety requirements and did not effectively manage the team and associated facilities.
The school's fault, which led to the above-mentioned incidents, caused great physical and psychological suffering and caused greater suffering to the family, is legally responsible.
In response, the school argued that the school had set up a safety net on the playground and posted regulations, training notices informing it that entering the playground was required to be safe from the training site and to be mindful of its own safety, and that the plaintiff had failed to prove that the school “had failed in its duty of safety and security”.
The court considered that the university involved in the incident was open to the public free of charge and that while the school had a duty of safety and security in the management of the playground, such an obligation of security was sufficient only to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school had set up a safety net on the playground, had fulfilled its due security obligations, and Chen Hwa also compensated Siu Man for various losses, such as medical expenses and transportation costs, in accordance with an earlier compensation agreement, and the parties agreed to resolve the dispute once and for all.
Later on, the parents reiterated their claim for school compensation, and the court ruled against the plaintiff's application in its entirety.
Neither of the parties appealed the sentence, which is now in force.
Under article 37 of our Tort Liability Act, schools, as administrators of public places, have an obligation to ensure their safety and security; in cases where the actions of third persons result in harm to others, third persons are liable for torts and public places managers who fail to meet their obligation to ensure their safety and security are subject to complementary liability.
The judge stated that since it was most likely, as the administrator of a public place, to have an understanding of the actual situation in the place, to foresee possible dangers and damage, and thus to take the necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of the loss or to mitigate the extent of the damage, and to avoid and mitigate the damage at the lowest cost, the law provided for a corresponding duty of protection for the performance of social activities.
In the present case, the obligation to ensure the safety and security of schools should be compatible with the social activities they are engaged in, in particular, the adoption of basic security measures and the duty to inform of hidden risks, in the case of people entering the playgrounds, which are open to the public free of charge.
Nor is it appropriate in judicial practice to impose excessive safety and security obligations on administrators of public places.
If the school has adopted a protective net and the obligation to inform is fulfilled, it may be held that the school is free of fault and is not legally liable.
In addition, in the case of third-party torts, even if the administrator of a public place, such as a school, fails to fulfil his duty of security, his liability is supplemented by damages, and under the recently promulgated Civil Code, the administrator may recover from the third person after assuming additional liability.
Therefore, in such an incident, the victim should not extend the scope of the claim after he or she has received compensation from the direct infringer.
