Increased Israeli surveillance of recurrent outbreaks of disease
Early in the outbreak of the new coronary pneumonia epidemic, Israel's control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of the ban on anti-control measures and the recent marked increase in the number of new coronary pneumonia cases in Israel, the Government of Israel has taken urgent measures on several occasions to strengthen the control of the epidemic.
On 28 February, the first case of new coronary pneumonia was diagnosed in Israel itself, prompting the closure of all ports of entry and exit, the suspension of non-essential trades, the conversion of schools to online instruction, restrictions on public transport and non-essential social activities, the closure of municipalities with severe epidemics, and joint military and police defence and control initiatives.
This series of measures quickly yielded positive results, with new cases of coronary pneumonia diagnosed in Israel falling to a single digits by mid-May.
As the epidemic is brought under control, Israel's anti-control measures have been completely lifted and the number of new confirmed cases of pneumonia has gradually rebounded since June.
The spread of the epidemic is accelerating, especially after July.
In recent days, Israel had more than 1,500 new cases per day for eight days, with 916 new cases as at 25 July.
As at 25 July, Israel had 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths.
In the face of the rapid resurgence of the epidemic, the Israeli Government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On 6 July, after more than 30,000 confirmed cases, the Government of Israel closed public entertainment facilities, such as gymnasiums, swimming pools, bars and nightclubs, and introduced a policy of restricting public transport to a maximum of 20 passengers per bus.
On 17 September, the Government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of the “enclosed city” on weekends, which provided for the implementation of the “envelope city” between 5 p.m. and 5 p.m. on Fridays a week.
During this period, the population may go out, but places such as shops, shopping malls, hairdressers, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition galleries, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while basic services such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, meetings of more than 10 persons are prohibited on all dates and periods, places such as gymnasiums, studios, etc. are closed, restaurants and cafés are prohibited and take-out services are permitted only.
At the same time, the Israeli population has not paid sufficient attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and has not been able to join forces with the Government in the fight against it.
In the wake of repeated outbreaks in Israel, many people went to the streets to protest against the impact of the Government's preventive measures on their economic interests.
On 11 July, tens of thousands of people demonstrated in Tel Aviv, arguing that the policy of combating the disease affected the economy.
In the evening of 21, thousands of protesters gathered in front of the residence of Prime Minister Netanyahu in Jerusalem to protest against the imposition by Prime Minister Netanyahu of preventive measures such as the ban on restaurants and cafés without commensurate compensation.
In addition, in order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people do not comply with the requirement to wear masks in their outdoor activities, etc., and many people wear masks only on their chins or on their wrists.
During the repeated periods of the epidemic, schools were the worst affected by the spread of the new crown virus, and a recent visit to the kindergarten by journalists found that neither kindergarten teachers nor students were wearing masks as required by the Government, nor were they able to maintain a two-metre safe social distance from each other, burying a large number of teachers and students with the virus.
Professor Elie Waxman, a member of the National Security Council's expert advisory mission to counter the epidemic, argued that Israel was moving towards a “dangerous situation”, noting that the current measures taken by Israel to prevent and control the epidemic were insufficient and that all recreational and recreational venues and summer schools should be closed in order to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman stated that Israel lacked an overall plan to combat the epidemic and that Parliament and government departments should move away from their respective interests as soon as possible and reach agreement on the fight against the epidemic, with clear steps to include relevant restrictions in different sectors.
The newspaper Tel Aviv, on July 25th, is a reporter in Tel Aviv, Wang Xing.
