The Lancet published praises China's anti-epidemic efforts and encourages countries to learn from their experiences.
According to the Journal 25 of The Lancet, China, a country with 1.4 billion people of similar size to Europe or the United States, has effectively controlled the new crown epidemic at this stage without further widespread transmission and has largely controlled the epidemic in the country.
According to the article, over a decade or so, China has invested heavily in domestic research and public health construction, making it much more prepared for the new crown than for the severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) of that year.
The author states that, at the time of the 2002 SARS outbreak, China was initially ill-prepared, and in particular the pathogens could not be identified.
When the new coronary virus was discovered in December 2019, Chinese scientists were soon able to identify the type of virus and to share genome sequencing data with the international community on 11 January 2020.
By the end of January, doctors from mainland China and Hong Kong had articulated the clinical characteristics of the virus, warning the world of the threat of the new coronary virus through research papers published in The Lancet.
China has also been at the forefront of vaccine research and, in the event of a state of emergency, through close domestic cooperation, conducted very rapidly and strictly. In May and July, respectively, the results of the early trials of the new crown vaccine developed by China were published in the Lancet.
China's experience had shown that it was important to invest in national health and research systems and to improve laboratory capacity effectively.
This is the basis for a rapid and effective national response to health emergencies and global health security.
Other countries, in particular low- and middle-income countries, are highly worthy of learning and learning.
Moreover, China's experience has shown that, on the basis of strong research, strong high-level determination to rely on scientific evidence for sound decision-making is essential if the new crown epidemic is to be brought under effective control.
The article stressed the need for Governments and their leaders to respect science, understand its value and act on it in the most socially beneficial manner.
In the early days of the outbreak, the Chinese National Guard appointed three teams of infectious disease experts to Wuhan to investigate the risk and spread of the new crown virus. Their recommendations provided the basis for the decision of 23 January to “sequete” Wuhan; when experts raised the need and urgency for the construction of the quadrant hospital, the Government took the decision and implemented it quickly; and, at the same time, the broad participation of the community and the population made it possible to control the epidemic quickly and effectively.
The article concluded by highlighting the need for countries to strengthen global cooperation and joint responses to global health emergencies.
